{"url": "https://www.reddit.com/r/learnprogramming/comments/9bajmt/help_with_incrementing_in_java/", "text": "For example:\n\nint a = 5;\n\nint b = 3;\n\nint c = a * b++; \\\\ c would equal 15\n\nint d = a * ++b; \\\\ d would equal 20\n\nWhat would be the purpose of a post increment if it doesn\u2019t do anything to the result (unless it does do something and I just didn\u2019t realize). \n\nSorry for this question, Im still very new to Java.\n\nEdit: thanks for the answers guys, helps a lot.", "score": 1, "comments": [{"body": "> What would be the purpose of a post increment if it doesn\u2019t do anything to the result\n\nBecause it changes the value of b for the next use.  So, instead of:\n\n    int c = a * b;\n    b += 1;\n\nYou can do the same thing in one line:\n\n    int c = a * b++;\n\nPersonally, though, I don't like these operators and prefer to not use them as it adds unnecessary confusion. ", "id": "e51jibm", "replies": []}, {"body": "in your code, d end up being 25 not 20.\n\nb++ increments b (but return the old value), so after the third line, b is 4, not 3.", "id": "e51iols", "replies": []}, {"body": "It changes the value of `b` before the next use.  And actually, in your code, it would make `d` equal 25:\n\n    int a = 5;\n    int b = 3;\n    int c = a * b++; // c = 5 * 3 = 15, b = 4 at end of statement\n    int d = a * ++b; // d = 5 * (4 + 1) = 25, b = 5 at end of statement", "id": "e51iv6w", "replies": []}], "title": "Help with incrementing in Java"}